The paper deals with geometric spanners, which are a fundamental topic in computational geometry, and specifically focuses on fault-tolerant additive weighted spanners. This makes cs.CG (Computational Geometry) the most likely category. The paper also involves algorithms and data structures for computing these spanners, which falls under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The use of weights and distances suggests cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as another possible category. The paper also involves graph theory and optimization, which are covered in cs.GR (Graph Theory) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis), respectively.
